% @category: Advanced Programmability & Terminal
% @name: Subnivean VM / Bytecode Assembly
% @description: A guide to the Subnivean stack machine
@cassilda: subnivean_guide
  The CL guide  teaches  how to write  Computational Lambdas – the  high-level la-
  nguage compiled by Hyades. This  companion guide goes one level deeper. Here you
  will learn what CL compiles 𝑑𝑜𝑤𝑛 𝑡𝑜: the raw bytecode executed by the  Subnivean
  virtual machine.
  
  Every example in this guide is 𝑙𝑖𝑣𝑒. The boxed assembly listings are not pseudo-
  code; they are real programs executed by \𝑠𝑛{…}, Hyades‘ inline  assembler. Each
  one runs inside the  typesetting engine and  produces the output  you see beside
  it.
  
  Subnivean  is  a 𝑠𝑡𝑎𝑐𝑘  𝑚𝑎𝑐ℎ𝑖𝑛𝑒. There are no registers.  Every value lives on a
  stack;  instructions pop their operands and push their results. If you have ever
  used an HP calculator in RPN  mode, or written  Forth, the model will feel fami-
  liar. If not, the first few sections will build the intuition from scratch.
  
  Why does Subnivean exist? Speed. The text-based macro  interpreter expands stri-
  ngs  character by character – fine for  formatting, but far too slow for Game of
  Life or Matrix  Digital Rain at interactive  frame rates. Subnivean  compiles to
  bytecode  and executes it in a tight C loop,  achieving a 65x speedup over inte-
  rpreted CL.
  
  The \𝑠𝑛{…} command feeds source text to a two-pass  assembler. Pass one collects
  labels and  constant-pool directives. Pass two emits instructions. The resulting
  bytecode is handed to the VM, which executes it and returns whatever was sent to
  OUTPUT as a string.
  
  The  sections build on each  other. By the end you will have  written a complete
  GCD  algorithm and an iterative  Fibonacci generator at the bytecode level – and
  you will know exactly what every instruction does.
  
  𝐓𝐡𝐞 𝐒𝐭𝐚𝐜𝐤
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  Everything in Subnivean  begins with  the stack.  PUSH_INT places an integer  on
  top;  OUTPUT pops  the top  value and sends it to the output  stream. HALT stops
  execution.
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  PUSH_INT 42                                                           │
  │ 2:  │  OUTPUT                                                                │
  │ 3:  │  HALT                                                                  │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
     ╭─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
  ╭──┴────────────╮                                                            │
  │ 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output │|··························································|│
  ╰──┬────────────╯                                                            │
     │   42                                                                   ░│
     ╰─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯
  
  That is a complete  program. PUSH_INT 42 pushes the  integer 42 onto the  stack.
  OUTPUT pops it, converts it to its string  representation, and appends it to the
  output buffer. HALT stops the VM.
  
  Instructions consume their operands by popping. After OUTPUT, the stack is empty
  again. Let us try arithmetic:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  PUSH_INT 5                                                            │
  │ 2:  │  PUSH_INT 3                                                            │
  │ 3:  │  ADD                                                                   │
  │ 4:  │  OUTPUT                                                                │
  │ 5:  │  HALT                                                                  │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
     ╭─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
  ╭──┴────────────╮                                                            │
  │ 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output │|··························································|│
  ╰──┬────────────╯                                                            │
     │   8                                                                    ░│
     ╰─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯
  
  PUSH_INT 5 pushes 5. PUSH_INT 3 pushes 3. Now the stack holds [5, 3] (3 on top).
  ADD pops both and pushes their sum: [8]. OUTPUT pops 8 and prints it.
  
                                    DUP and POP
                                  o═════════════o
  
  DUP duplicates the top of stack. POP discards it.
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  PUSH_INT 10                                                           │
  │ 2:  │  DUP                                                                   │
  │ 3:  │  ADD                                                                   │
  │ 4:  │  OUTPUT                                                                │
  │ 5:  │  HALT                                                                  │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
     ╭─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
  ╭──┴────────────╮                                                            │
  │ 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output │|··························································|│
  ╰──┬────────────╯                                                            │
     │   20                                                                   ░│
     ╰─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯
  
  DUP copies 10, giving [10, 10]. ADD produces [20].
  
                                    SWAP and ROT
                                  o══════════════o
  
  SWAP  exchanges the top two elements. ROT rotates the top three: [a, b, c] beco-
  mes [b, c, a].
  
  Order matters for  non-commutative operations. SUB pops [b, a] and  computes a -
  b. If you push 10 then 3, you get 10 - 3 = 7:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  PUSH_INT 10                                                           │
  │ 2:  │  PUSH_INT 3                                                            │
  │ 3:  │  SUB                                                                   │
  │ 4:  │  OUTPUT                                                                │
  │ 5:  │  HALT                                                                  │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
     ╭─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
  ╭──┴────────────╮                                                            │
  │ 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output │|··························································|│
  ╰──┬────────────╯                                                            │
     │   7                                                                    ░│
     ╰─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯
  
  But if you need 3 - 10, push them in the  opposite order – or use SWAP after pu-
  shing:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  PUSH_INT 10                                                           │
  │ 2:  │  PUSH_INT 3                                                            │
  │ 3:  │  SWAP                                                                  │
  │ 4:  │  SUB                                                                   │
  │ 5:  │  OUTPUT                                                                │
  │ 6:  │  HALT                                                                  │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
     ╭─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
  ╭──┴────────────╮                                                            │
  │ 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output │|··························································|│
  ╰──┬────────────╯                                                            │
     │   -7                                                                   ░│
     ╰─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯
                                   Special Values
                                 o════════════════o
  
  PUSH_NIL pushes a nil value. PUSH_TRUE pushes integer 1. PUSH_FALSE pushes inte-
  ger 0. Booleans in Subnivean  are  just integers:  any nonzero  value is truthy,
  zero is falsy.
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  PUSH_TRUE                                                             │
  │ 2:  │  PUSH_FALSE                                                            │
  │ 3:  │  ADD                                                                   │
  │ 4:  │  OUTPUT                                                                │
  │ 5:  │  HALT                                                                  │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
     ╭─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
  ╭──┴────────────╮                                                            │
  │ 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output │|··························································|│
  ╰──┬────────────╯                                                            │
     │   1                                                                    ░│
     ╰─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯
  
  True (1) plus false (0) equals 1.
  
            ............................................................
                                    STACK DEPTH
  
            The  Subnivean stack is 4096 entries deep – more than enough
            for any  computation. A stack  overflow halts the VM with an
            error.
            ............................................................
  
  
  𝐀𝐫𝐢𝐭𝐡𝐦𝐞𝐭𝐢𝐜
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  Subnivean  provides six arithmetic  operations. All binary operators pop two va-
  lues [b, a] and push the result. The 𝑓𝑖𝑟𝑠𝑡 value pushed is the left operand:
  
    ● 𝐀𝐃𝐃: a + b
    ● 𝐒𝐔𝐁: a - b
    ● 𝐌𝐔𝐋: a * b
    ● 𝐃𝐈𝐕: a / b (integer, truncates toward zero)
    ● 𝐌𝐎𝐃: a mod b (remainder)
    ● 𝐍𝐄𝐆: unary negation (one operand)
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  ; Multiplication: 6 * 7 = 42                                          │
  │ 2:  │  PUSH_INT 6                                                            │
  │ 3:  │  PUSH_INT 7                                                            │
  │ 4:  │  MUL                                                                   │
  │ 5:  │  OUTPUT                                                                │
  │ 6:  │  HALT                                                                  │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
     ╭─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
  ╭──┴────────────╮                                                            │
  │ 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output │|··························································|│
  ╰──┬────────────╯                                                            │
     │   42                                                                   ░│
     ╰─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  ; Division: 20 / 3 = 6 (truncated)                                    │
  │ 2:  │  PUSH_INT 20                                                           │
  │ 3:  │  PUSH_INT 3                                                            │
  │ 4:  │  DIV                                                                   │
  │ 5:  │  OUTPUT                                                                │
  │ 6:  │  HALT                                                                  │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
     ╭─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
  ╭──┴────────────╮                                                            │
  │ 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output │|··························································|│
  ╰──┬────────────╯                                                            │
     │   6                                                                    ░│
     ╰─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  ; Modulo: 17 mod 5 = 2                                                │
  │ 2:  │  PUSH_INT 17                                                           │
  │ 3:  │  PUSH_INT 5                                                            │
  │ 4:  │  MOD                                                                   │
  │ 5:  │  OUTPUT                                                                │
  │ 6:  │  HALT                                                                  │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
     ╭─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
  ╭──┴────────────╮                                                            │
  │ 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output │|··························································|│
  ╰──┬────────────╯                                                            │
     │   2                                                                    ░│
     ╰─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯
  
  NEG takes a single operand and negates it:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  PUSH_INT 42                                                           │
  │ 2:  │  NEG                                                                   │
  │ 3:  │  OUTPUT                                                                │
  │ 4:  │  HALT                                                                  │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
     ╭─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
  ╭──┴────────────╮                                                            │
  │ 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output │|··························································|│
  ╰──┬────────────╯                                                            │
     │   -42                                                                  ░│
     ╰─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯
  
            ............................................................
                                 INTEGER PRECISION
  
            All values are 64-bit signed integers. Integer division tru-
            ncates  toward zero. There are no floating-point  numbers in
            Subnivean.
            ............................................................
  
  
  𝐂𝐨𝐧𝐬𝐭𝐚𝐧𝐭𝐬 𝐚𝐧𝐝 𝐒𝐭𝐫𝐢𝐧𝐠𝐬
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  Integers  are pushed with  PUSH_INT. But what about strings? Strings live in the
  𝑐𝑜𝑛𝑠𝑡𝑎𝑛𝑡 𝑝𝑜𝑜𝑙 – a per-function  array of compile- time values. The assembler di-
  rective .𝐜𝐨𝐧𝐬𝐭 adds a string:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  .const "hello"       ; index 0                                        │
  │ 2:  │  .const "world"       ; index 1                                        │
  │ 3:  │  PUSH_CONST 0         ; push "hello"                                   │
  │ 4:  │  PUSH_CONST 1         ; push "world"                                   │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
  
  The first  .const gets index 0, the  second gets index 1, and so on.  PUSH_CONST
  loads from the constant pool by index.
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  .const "hello"                                                        │
  │ 2:  │  PUSH_CONST 0                                                          │
  │ 3:  │  OUTPUT                                                                │
  │ 4:  │  HALT                                                                  │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
     ╭─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
  ╭──┴────────────╮                                                            │
  │ 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output │|··························································|│
  ╰──┬────────────╯                                                            │
     │   hello                                                                ░│
     ╰─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯
                                String Concatenation
                              o══════════════════════o
  
  CONCAT pops two strings [b, a] and pushes their concatenation a+b:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  .const "hello "                                                       │
  │ 2:  │  .const "world"                                                        │
  │ 3:  │  PUSH_CONST 0                                                          │
  │ 4:  │  PUSH_CONST 1                                                          │
  │ 5:  │  CONCAT                                                                │
  │ 6:  │  OUTPUT                                                                │
  │ 7:  │  HALT                                                                  │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
     ╭─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
  ╭──┴────────────╮                                                            │
  │ 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output │|··························································|│
  ╰──┬────────────╯                                                            │
     │   hello world                                                          ░│
     ╰─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯
                                     STRINGIFY
                                   o═══════════o
  
  STRINGIFY  converts any value to its string  representation. This is how you mix
  integers and strings:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  .const " is the answer"                                               │
  │ 2:  │  PUSH_INT 42                                                           │
  │ 3:  │  STRINGIFY                                                             │
  │ 4:  │  PUSH_CONST 0                                                          │
  │ 5:  │  CONCAT                                                                │
  │ 6:  │  OUTPUT                                                                │
  │ 7:  │  HALT                                                                  │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
     ╭─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
  ╭──┴────────────╮                                                            │
  │ 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output │|··························································|│
  ╰──┬────────────╯                                                            │
     │   42 is the answer                                                     ░│
     ╰─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯
                                  Escape Sequences
                                o══════════════════o
  
  Strings in .const support standard escape sequences:
  
    ● \\n – newline
    ● \\t – tab
    ● \\\\ – literal backslash
    ● \\" – literal double quote
                               Constant Pool Indexing
                             o════════════════════════o
  
  Pool  indices  are assigned  sequentially. Both  .const and .sym  (covered next)
  share the same pool. The first  directive is index 0, the second is index 1, re-
  gardless of whether it is .const or .sym. Plan your indices accordingly.
  
            ............................................................
                              OUTPUT ACCEPTS ANYTHING
  
            OUTPUT calls STRINGIFY internally. You can OUTPUT an integer
            directly  without explicit  STRINGIFY – it will be converted
            automatically.  STRINGIFY is needed  when you want to CONCAT
            an integer with a string.
            ............................................................
  
  
  𝐒𝐲𝐦𝐛𝐨𝐥𝐬 𝐚𝐧𝐝 𝐁𝐢𝐧𝐝𝐢𝐧𝐠𝐬
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  Variables in Subnivean are 𝑏𝑖𝑛𝑑𝑖𝑛𝑔𝑠: a symbol (the name) associated with a value
  in a 𝑠𝑐𝑜𝑝𝑒. The assembler provides the .sym directive to intern a symbol:
  
  ┌────────────────┬─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │            1:  │  .sym x ; intern symbol "x", add to constant pool           │
  └────────────────┴─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
  
  Like .const, .sym  occupies a constant  pool slot. The  difference is that  .sym
  creates an interned 𝑠𝑦𝑚𝑏𝑜𝑙 – a unique identity used for fast variable lookup.
  
  Three instructions work with bindings:
  
    ● 𝐁𝐈𝐍𝐃: [value, sym] → [] – bind value to symbol in current scope
    ● 𝐋𝐎𝐎𝐊𝐔𝐏: [sym] → [value] – search scope chain for symbol
    ● 𝐒𝐄𝐓: [value, sym] → [] – update existing binding in chain
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  .sym x                                                                │
  │ 2:  │  PUSH_INT 42                                                           │
  │ 3:  │  PUSH_CONST 0                                                          │
  │ 4:  │  BIND                                                                  │
  │ 5:  │  PUSH_CONST 0                                                          │
  │ 6:  │  LOOKUP                                                                │
  │ 7:  │  OUTPUT                                                                │
  │ 8:  │  HALT                                                                  │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
     ╭─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
  ╭──┴────────────╮                                                            │
  │ 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output │|··························································|│
  ╰──┬────────────╯                                                            │
     │   42                                                                   ░│
     ╰─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯
  
  Step by step: .sym x interns  “x” at pool index 0. PUSH_INT 42 pushes the value.
  PUSH_CONST 0 pushes the  symbol. BIND pops  both and stores the  binding x=42 in
  the  current scope. Then  PUSH_CONST 0 pushes the symbol again, LOOKUP finds it,
  and OUTPUT prints 42.
  
  SET updates an existing binding without creating a new one:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  .sym x                                                                │
  │ 2:  │  PUSH_INT 10                                                           │
  │ 3:  │  PUSH_CONST 0                                                          │
  │ 4:  │  BIND                                                                  │
  │ 5:  │  PUSH_INT 99                                                           │
  │ 6:  │  PUSH_CONST 0                                                          │
  │ 7:  │  SET                                                                   │
  │ 8:  │  PUSH_CONST 0                                                          │
  │ 9:  │  LOOKUP                                                                │
  │ 10: │  OUTPUT                                                                │
  │ 11: │  HALT                                                                  │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
     ╭─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
  ╭──┴────────────╮                                                            │
  │ 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output │|··························································|│
  ╰──┬────────────╯                                                            │
     │   99                                                                   ░│
     ╰─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯
  
  First x is bound to 10, then SET overwrites it with 99.
  
            ............................................................
                                    WHY SYMBOLS?
  
            Symbols are  𝑖𝑛𝑡𝑒𝑟𝑛𝑒𝑑 – each unique name exists exactly once
            in  memory.  Comparing two  symbols is a pointer  comparison
            (O(1)), not a string comparison (O(n)). This is why variable
            lookup is fast.
            ............................................................
  
  
  𝐂𝐞𝐥𝐥𝐬 – 𝐌𝐮𝐭𝐚𝐛𝐥𝐞 𝐁𝐨𝐱𝐞𝐬
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  Subnivean values are  immutable. An integer on the  stack is just a number – you
  cannot  increment it in place. But  programs need mutable state. The solution is
  𝑐𝑒𝑙𝑙𝑠: mutable boxes that wrap a value.
  
    ● 𝐂𝐄𝐋𝐋_𝐍𝐄𝐖: [value] → [cell] – box the value
    ● 𝐂𝐄𝐋𝐋_𝐆𝐄𝐓: [cell] → [value] – unbox (copy the contents)
    ● 𝐂𝐄𝐋𝐋_𝐒𝐄𝐓: [value, cell] → [] – mutate the contents
    ● 𝐂𝐄𝐋𝐋_𝐈𝐍𝐂: [cell] → [new_val] – increment integer in cell, push new value
    ● 𝐂𝐄𝐋𝐋_𝐃𝐄𝐂: [cell] → [new_val] – decrement integer in cell, push new value
  
  The canonical pattern for a mutable variable:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  ; Create mutable variable x = 5                                       │
  │ 2:  │  .sym x                                                                │
  │ 3:  │  PUSH_INT 5          ; value                                           │
  │ 4:  │  CELL_NEW            ; wrap in cell                                    │
  │ 5:  │  PUSH_CONST 0        ; symbol                                          │
  │ 6:  │  BIND                ; bind cell to symbol                             │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
  
  To read the variable, look up the cell, then CELL_GET. To mutate it, look up the
  cell, then CELL_SET (or CELL_INC/CELL_DEC):
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  .sym x                                                                │
  │ 2:  │  PUSH_INT 5                                                            │
  │ 3:  │  CELL_NEW                                                              │
  │ 4:  │  PUSH_CONST 0                                                          │
  │ 5:  │  BIND                                                                  │
  │ 6:  │  ; read x                                                              │
  │ 7:  │  PUSH_CONST 0                                                          │
  │ 8:  │  LOOKUP                                                                │
  │ 9:  │  CELL_GET                                                              │
  │ 10: │  OUTPUT                                                                │
  │ 11: │  HALT                                                                  │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
     ╭─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
  ╭──┴────────────╮                                                            │
  │ 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output │|··························································|│
  ╰──┬────────────╯                                                            │
     │   5                                                                    ░│
     ╰─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯
  
  CELL_INC  increments the integer inside a cell and pushes the new value. Here we
  increment x five times:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  .sym x                                                                │
  │ 2:  │  PUSH_INT 0                                                            │
  │ 3:  │  CELL_NEW                                                              │
  │ 4:  │  PUSH_CONST 0                                                          │
  │ 5:  │  BIND                                                                  │
  │ 6:  │  ; increment 5 times                                                   │
  │ 7:  │  PUSH_CONST 0                                                          │
  │ 8:  │  LOOKUP                                                                │
  │ 9:  │  CELL_INC                                                              │
  │ 10: │  POP                                                                   │
  │ 11: │  PUSH_CONST 0                                                          │
  │ 12: │  LOOKUP                                                                │
  │ 13: │  CELL_INC                                                              │
  │ 14: │  POP                                                                   │
  │ 15: │  PUSH_CONST 0                                                          │
  │ 16: │  LOOKUP                                                                │
  │ 17: │  CELL_INC                                                              │
  │ 18: │  POP                                                                   │
  │ 19: │  PUSH_CONST 0                                                          │
  │ 20: │  LOOKUP                                                                │
  │ 21: │  CELL_INC                                                              │
  │ 22: │  POP                                                                   │
  │ 23: │  PUSH_CONST 0                                                          │
  │ 24: │  LOOKUP                                                                │
  │ 25: │  CELL_INC                                                              │
  │ 26: │  OUTPUT                                                                │
  │ 27: │  HALT                                                                  │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
     ╭─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
  ╭──┴────────────╮                                                            │
  │ 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output │|··························································|│
  ╰──┬────────────╯                                                            │
     │   5                                                                    ░│
     ╰─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯
  
  We  start at 0 and  increment five  times; the final  CELL_INC pushes  5,  which
  OUTPUT prints. Each intermediate CELL_INC result is discarded with POP.
  
            ............................................................
                                    CELLS AND CL
  
            In  CL,  \𝑙𝑒𝑡<x:int>{5} compiles  to  exactly:  PUSH_INT 5 /
            CELL_NEW / PUSH_CONST <sym_x> / BIND. Every mutable variable
            is a cell. Reading {x} compiles to LOOKUP / CELL_GET.
            ............................................................
  
  
  𝐂𝐨𝐦𝐩𝐚𝐫𝐢𝐬𝐨𝐧 𝐚𝐧𝐝 𝐋𝐨𝐠𝐢𝐜
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  Subnivean provides six  comparison operators and three logic  operators. All co-
  mparisons pop [b, a] and push 1 (true) or 0 (false):
  
    ● 𝐄𝐐: a == b
    ● 𝐍𝐄: a != b
    ● 𝐋𝐓: a < b
    ● 𝐆𝐓: a > b
    ● 𝐋𝐄: a <= b
    ● 𝐆𝐄: a >= b
  
  Logic operators:
  
    ● 𝐀𝐍𝐃: a && b (non-short-circuit)
    ● 𝐎𝐑: a || b
    ● 𝐍𝐎𝐓: !a (unary)
  
  Results are plain integers. 1 is true, 0 is false:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  ; 10 < 20?                                                            │
  │ 2:  │  PUSH_INT 10                                                           │
  │ 3:  │  PUSH_INT 20                                                           │
  │ 4:  │  LT                                                                    │
  │ 5:  │  OUTPUT                                                                │
  │ 6:  │  HALT                                                                  │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
     ╭─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
  ╭──┴────────────╮                                                            │
  │ 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output │|··························································|│
  ╰──┬────────────╯                                                            │
     │   1                                                                    ░│
     ╰─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  ; 5 == 5?                                                             │
  │ 2:  │  PUSH_INT 5                                                            │
  │ 3:  │  PUSH_INT 5                                                            │
  │ 4:  │  EQ                                                                    │
  │ 5:  │  OUTPUT                                                                │
  │ 6:  │  HALT                                                                  │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
     ╭─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
  ╭──┴────────────╮                                                            │
  │ 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output │|··························································|│
  ╰──┬────────────╯                                                            │
     │   1                                                                    ░│
     ╰─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  ; NOT 0 = 1                                                           │
  │ 2:  │  PUSH_FALSE                                                            │
  │ 3:  │  NOT                                                                   │
  │ 4:  │  OUTPUT                                                                │
  │ 5:  │  HALT                                                                  │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
     ╭─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
  ╭──┴────────────╮                                                            │
  │ 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output │|··························································|│
  ╰──┬────────────╯                                                            │
     │   1                                                                    ░│
     ╰─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯
  
  These are the building blocks for control flow, which follows next.
  
  
  𝐂𝐨𝐧𝐭𝐫𝐨𝐥 𝐅𝐥𝐨𝐰
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  Without jumps, programs execute top to bottom. Labels and jump  instructions add
  branching and loops.
  
                                       Labels
                                     o════════o
  
  A label is an identifier followed by a colon. It marks a position in the instru-
  ction stream:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  start:                ; defines label "start"                         │
  │ 2:  │      PUSH_INT 1                                                        │
  │ 3:  │  done:                 ; defines label "done"                          │
  │ 4:  │      HALT                                                              │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
  
  Labels do not emit  instructions – they are resolved by the assembler and conve-
  rted to relative offsets.
  
                                 Jump Instructions
                               o═══════════════════o
    ● 𝐉𝐔𝐌𝐏 𝐥𝐚𝐛𝐞𝐥: unconditional jump
    ● 𝐉𝐔𝐌𝐏_𝐈𝐅 𝐥𝐚𝐛𝐞𝐥: [cond] → [] – jump if truthy (nonzero)
    ● 𝐉𝐔𝐌𝐏_𝐔𝐍𝐋𝐄𝐒𝐒 𝐥𝐚𝐛𝐞𝐥: [cond] → [] – jump if falsy (zero)
    ● 𝐋𝐎𝐎𝐏 𝐥𝐚𝐛𝐞𝐥: backward jump (for loops)
                                  If/Else Pattern
                                o═════════════════o
  
  The classic conditional: test a condition, jump to one branch or the other.
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  .const "yes"                                                          │
  │ 2:  │  .const "no"                                                           │
  │ 3:  │  ; Is 10 > 5?                                                          │
  │ 4:  │  PUSH_INT 10                                                           │
  │ 5:  │  PUSH_INT 5                                                            │
  │ 6:  │  GT                                                                    │
  │ 7:  │  JUMP_IF yes                                                           │
  │ 8:  │  ; false branch                                                        │
  │ 9:  │  PUSH_CONST 1                                                          │
  │ 10: │  JUMP end                                                              │
  │ 11: │  yes:                                                                  │
  │ 12: │  PUSH_CONST 0                                                          │
  │ 13: │  end:                                                                  │
  │ 14: │  OUTPUT                                                                │
  │ 15: │  HALT                                                                  │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
     ╭─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
  ╭──┴────────────╮                                                            │
  │ 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output │|··························································|│
  ╰──┬────────────╯                                                            │
     │   yes                                                                  ░│
     ╰─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯
  
  GT pushes 1 (10 > 5 is true). JUMP_IF pops it and jumps to 𝑦𝑒𝑠. The string “yes”
  is pushed and printed.
  
                              A Simple Countdown Loop
                            o═════════════════════════o
  
  Loops use LOOP for backward jumps. Here is a countdown from 5 to 1:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  .sym n                                                                │
  │ 2:  │  .const " "                                                            │
  │ 3:  │  ; n = 5 (as cell)                                                     │
  │ 4:  │  PUSH_INT 5                                                            │
  │ 5:  │  CELL_NEW                                                              │
  │ 6:  │  PUSH_CONST 0                                                          │
  │ 7:  │  BIND                                                                  │
  │ 8:  │  loop:                                                                 │
  │ 9:  │    ; output n                                                          │
  │ 10: │    PUSH_CONST 0                                                        │
  │ 11: │    LOOKUP                                                              │
  │ 12: │    CELL_GET                                                            │
  │ 13: │    OUTPUT                                                              │
  │ 14: │    ; output space                                                      │
  │ 15: │    PUSH_CONST 1                                                        │
  │ 16: │    OUTPUT                                                              │
  │ 17: │    ; decrement n                                                       │
  │ 18: │    PUSH_CONST 0                                                        │
  │ 19: │    LOOKUP                                                              │
  │ 20: │    CELL_DEC                                                            │
  │ 21: │    ; if n > 0, continue                                                │
  │ 22: │    PUSH_INT 0                                                          │
  │ 23: │    GT                                                                  │
  │ 24: │    JUMP_IF loop                                                        │
  │ 25: │  HALT                                                                  │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
     ╭─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
  ╭──┴────────────╮                                                            │
  │ 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output │|··························································|│
  ╰──┬────────────╯                                                            │
     │   5 4 3 2 1                                                            ░│
     ╰─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯
  
  CELL_DEC  decrements the cell and  pushes the new value. We compare  that with 0
  using GT. If still positive, JUMP_IF loops back.
  
                                    Sum 1 to 10
                                  o═════════════o
  
  A slightly more involved loop that computes 1+2+…+10 = 55:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  .sym sum                                                              │
  │ 2:  │  .sym i                                                                │
  │ 3:  │  ; sum = 0                                                             │
  │ 4:  │  PUSH_INT 0                                                            │
  │ 5:  │  CELL_NEW                                                              │
  │ 6:  │  PUSH_CONST 0                                                          │
  │ 7:  │  BIND                                                                  │
  │ 8:  │  ; i = 1                                                               │
  │ 9:  │  PUSH_INT 1                                                            │
  │ 10: │  CELL_NEW                                                              │
  │ 11: │  PUSH_CONST 1                                                          │
  │ 12: │  BIND                                                                  │
  │ 13: │  loop:                                                                 │
  │ 14: │    ; sum += i                                                          │
  │ 15: │    PUSH_CONST 1                                                        │
  │ 16: │    LOOKUP                                                              │
  │ 17: │    CELL_GET                                                            │
  │ 18: │    PUSH_CONST 0                                                        │
  │ 19: │    LOOKUP                                                              │
  │ 20: │    CELL_GET                                                            │
  │ 21: │    ADD                                                                 │
  │ 22: │    PUSH_CONST 0                                                        │
  │ 23: │    LOOKUP                                                              │
  │ 24: │    CELL_SET                                                            │
  │ 25: │    ; i++                                                               │
  │ 26: │    PUSH_CONST 1                                                        │
  │ 27: │    LOOKUP                                                              │
  │ 28: │    CELL_INC                                                            │
  │ 29: │    ; if i <= 10, loop                                                  │
  │ 30: │    PUSH_INT 10                                                         │
  │ 31: │    LE                                                                  │
  │ 32: │    JUMP_IF loop                                                        │
  │ 33: │  ; output sum                                                          │
  │ 34: │  PUSH_CONST 0                                                          │
  │ 35: │  LOOKUP                                                                │
  │ 36: │  CELL_GET                                                              │
  │ 37: │  OUTPUT                                                                │
  │ 38: │  HALT                                                                  │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
     ╭─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
  ╭──┴────────────╮                                                            │
  │ 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output │|··························································|│
  ╰──┬────────────╯                                                            │
     │   55                                                                   ░│
     ╰─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯
                               The Two Loop Patterns
                             o═══════════════════════o
  
  𝐵𝑜𝑡𝑡𝑜𝑚-𝑡𝑒𝑠𝑡𝑒𝑑  (do-while): the body always executes at least once. The condition
  comes after the body:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  loop:                                                                 │
  │ 2:  │      ; ... body ...                                                    │
  │ 3:  │      ; ... condition ...                                               │
  │ 4:  │      JUMP_IF loop         ; repeat while true                          │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
  
  𝑇𝑜𝑝-𝑡𝑒𝑠𝑡𝑒𝑑  (while): the condition is checked  before the body. If false initia-
  lly, the body never executes:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  loop:                                                                 │
  │ 2:  │      ; ... condition ...                                               │
  │ 3:  │      JUMP_UNLESS done     ; exit if false                              │
  │ 4:  │      ; ... body ...                                                    │
  │ 5:  │      JUMP loop                                                         │
  │ 6:  │  done:                                                                 │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
  
            ............................................................
                                 LABELS AND OFFSETS
  
            JUMP, JUMP_IF, and JUMP_UNLESS use 𝑟𝑒𝑙𝑎𝑡𝑖𝑣𝑒 offsets interna-
            lly, but the  assembler computes them from label  names. You
            never need to count instructions by hand. Forward references
            work – you can JUMP_IF done before done: is defined.
            ............................................................
  
  
  𝐒𝐜𝐨𝐩𝐞𝐬
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  Subnivean organizes bindings into a 𝑠𝑐𝑜𝑝𝑒 𝑐ℎ𝑎𝑖𝑛. Each scope has a parent; LOOKUP
  searches up the chain.
  
    ● 𝐒𝐂𝐎𝐏𝐄_𝐍𝐄𝐖: create a child scope of the current one, enter it
    ● 𝐒𝐂𝐎𝐏𝐄_𝐏𝐎𝐏: exit to parent (child freed if no references remain)
    ● 𝐒𝐂𝐎𝐏𝐄_𝐂𝐀𝐏𝐓𝐔𝐑𝐄: push the current scope as a value
    ● 𝐒𝐂𝐎𝐏𝐄_𝐑𝐄𝐒𝐓𝐎𝐑𝐄: pop a scope value, make it current
  
  Scopes let you shadow variables without losing the outer binding:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  .sym x                                                                │
  │ 2:  │  .const " "                                                            │
  │ 3:  │  ; x = 10 in outer scope                                               │
  │ 4:  │  PUSH_INT 10                                                           │
  │ 5:  │  PUSH_CONST 0                                                          │
  │ 6:  │  BIND                                                                  │
  │ 7:  │  ; enter new scope                                                     │
  │ 8:  │  SCOPE_NEW                                                             │
  │ 9:  │  ; x = 99 in inner scope (shadows outer)                               │
  │ 10: │  PUSH_INT 99                                                           │
  │ 11: │  PUSH_CONST 0                                                          │
  │ 12: │  BIND                                                                  │
  │ 13: │  ; read inner x                                                        │
  │ 14: │  PUSH_CONST 0                                                          │
  │ 15: │  LOOKUP                                                                │
  │ 16: │  OUTPUT                                                                │
  │ 17: │  PUSH_CONST 1                                                          │
  │ 18: │  OUTPUT                                                                │
  │ 19: │  ; exit inner scope                                                    │
  │ 20: │  SCOPE_POP                                                             │
  │ 21: │  ; read outer x (still 10)                                             │
  │ 22: │  PUSH_CONST 0                                                          │
  │ 23: │  LOOKUP                                                                │
  │ 24: │  OUTPUT                                                                │
  │ 25: │  HALT                                                                  │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
     ╭─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
  ╭──┴────────────╮                                                            │
  │ 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output │|··························································|│
  ╰──┬────────────╯                                                            │
     │   99 10                                                                ░│
     ╰─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯
  
  The inner scope binds x=99, which  shadows the outer x=10. After  SCOPE_POP, the
  inner scope is destroyed and x resolves to 10 again.
  
            ............................................................
                                 WHY SCOPES MATTER
  
            Closures  capture scopes. In CL loops,  per-iteration scopes
            give each closure its own variables – the “JavaScript let in
            for-loop”  semantics that prevent the classic “all  closures
            share one counter” bug.
            ............................................................
  
  
  𝐅𝐮𝐧𝐜𝐭𝐢𝐨𝐧𝐬 𝐚𝐧𝐝 𝐂𝐥𝐨𝐬𝐮𝐫𝐞𝐬
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  Subnivean  supports  first-class closures: a function  paired with the  scope in
  which it was created.
  
    ● 𝐂𝐋𝐎𝐒𝐔𝐑𝐄: [scope] → [closure] – wraps a function (by constant pool index)
      with a captured scope
    ● 𝐂𝐀𝐋𝐋: [args…, closure] → [result] – call with operand = argc
    ● 𝐑𝐄𝐓𝐔𝐑𝐍: return nil from current function
    ● 𝐑𝐄𝐓𝐔𝐑𝐍_𝐕𝐀𝐋: [value] → ; return TOS
    ● 𝐓𝐀𝐈𝐋_𝐂𝐀𝐋𝐋: like CALL but reuses the stack frame (optimization)
  
  Creating a closure requires a compiled sub-function stored in the constant pool.
  The \𝑠𝑛{} assembler compiles a single flat function, so closures cannot be demo-
  nstrated in raw assembly. However, the mechanism is straightforward:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  ; How CL compiles a closure:                                          │
  │ 2:  │  ; 1. The lambda body is compiled to a Function                        │
  │ 3:  │  ;    and stored in the constant pool at some index N                  │
  │ 4:  │  ; 2. At the call site:                                                │
  │ 5:  │  SCOPE_CAPTURE        ; push current scope                             │
  │ 6:  │  CLOSURE N            ; wrap function N with scope -> closure          │
  │ 7:  │  CALL 0               ; call with 0 arguments                          │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
  
  When  CALL  executes, the VM creates a new  call frame, pushes  arguments into a
  child  scope of the  captured scope, and transfers control.  RETURN_VAL pops the
  result and passes it back to the caller.
  
            ............................................................
                                COMPILATION PATTERN
  
            Every #{…} lambda body  compiles to a Function stored in the
            parent’s  constant  pool.  \𝑖𝑛𝑣𝑜𝑘𝑒  emits   SCOPE_CAPTURE  /
            PUSH_CONST / CLOSURE / CALL. Arguments are pushed before the
            closure, and the CALL operand indicates how many there are.
            ............................................................
  
  
  𝐀𝐫𝐫𝐚𝐲𝐬
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  Subnivean arrays live in a persistent store and are accessed by address.
  
    ● 𝐀𝐑𝐑𝐀𝐘_𝐍𝐄𝐖: [elems…] → [array] – operand = element count
    ● 𝐀𝐑𝐑𝐀𝐘_𝐆𝐄𝐓: [idx, arr] → [elem]
    ● 𝐀𝐑𝐑𝐀𝐘_𝐒𝐄𝐓: [val, idx, arr] → []
    ● 𝐀𝐑𝐑𝐀𝐘_𝐋𝐄𝐍: [arr] → [len]
    ● 𝐀𝐑𝐑𝐀𝐘_𝐏𝐔𝐒𝐇: [val, arr] → []
    ● 𝐀𝐑𝐑𝐀𝐘_𝐏𝐎𝐏: [arr] → [val]
  
  Create an array with three elements and read the second one (index 1):
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  ; Create array [10, 20, 30]                                           │
  │ 2:  │  PUSH_INT 10                                                           │
  │ 3:  │  PUSH_INT 20                                                           │
  │ 4:  │  PUSH_INT 30                                                           │
  │ 5:  │  ARRAY_NEW 3                                                           │
  │ 6:  │  ; Read element at index 1                                             │
  │ 7:  │  DUP                                                                   │
  │ 8:  │  PUSH_INT 1                                                            │
  │ 9:  │  ARRAY_GET                                                             │
  │ 10: │  OUTPUT                                                                │
  │ 11: │  HALT                                                                  │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
     ╭─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
  ╭──┴────────────╮                                                            │
  │ 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output │|··························································|│
  ╰──┬────────────╯                                                            │
     │   20                                                                   ░│
     ╰─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯
  
  ARRAY_NEW 3 pops  three values and  creates an array  [10, 20, 30],  pushing its
  address. We DUP the address (we will need it), push index 1, and  ARRAY_GET pops
  idx then arr, producing 20.
  
                                    Push and Pop
                                  o══════════════o
  
  ARRAY_PUSH appends a value; ARRAY_POP removes and returns the last:
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  ; Create empty array                                                  │
  │ 2:  │  ARRAY_NEW 0                                                           │
  │ 3:  │  ; Push 100, 200, 300                                                  │
  │ 4:  │  DUP                                                                   │
  │ 5:  │  PUSH_INT 100                                                          │
  │ 6:  │  ARRAY_PUSH                                                            │
  │ 7:  │  DUP                                                                   │
  │ 8:  │  PUSH_INT 200                                                          │
  │ 9:  │  ARRAY_PUSH                                                            │
  │ 10: │  DUP                                                                   │
  │ 11: │  PUSH_INT 300                                                          │
  │ 12: │  ARRAY_PUSH                                                            │
  │ 13: │  ; Get length                                                          │
  │ 14: │  DUP                                                                   │
  │ 15: │  ARRAY_LEN                                                             │
  │ 16: │  OUTPUT                                                                │
  │ 17: │  HALT                                                                  │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
     ╭─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
  ╭──┴────────────╮                                                            │
  │ 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output │|··························································|│
  ╰──┬────────────╯                                                            │
     │   3                                                                    ░│
     ╰─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯
  
  We push three  elements onto an initially  empty array, then  ARRAY_LEN confirms
  the count is 3.
  
  Note the pattern:  ARRAY_PUSH pops val  (top) then arr  (second), so we DUP  the
  array address, push the value, and call ARRAY_PUSH.
  
  
  𝐌𝐚𝐩𝐬
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  Maps are  Robin Hood hash  tables in the  persistent store. Keys and  values are
  integers.
  
    ● 𝐌𝐀𝐏_𝐍𝐄𝐖: [] → [addr] – create empty map
    ● 𝐌𝐀𝐏_𝐒𝐄𝐓: [val, key, addr] → [] – set map[key] = val
    ● 𝐌𝐀𝐏_𝐆𝐄𝐓: [key, addr] → [value] – get map[key] (0 if missing)
    ● 𝐌𝐀𝐏_𝐇𝐀𝐒: [key, addr] → [0/1] – check if key exists
    ● 𝐌𝐀𝐏_𝐃𝐄𝐋: [key, addr] → [0/1] – delete key
    ● 𝐌𝐀𝐏_𝐋𝐄𝐍: [addr] → [count]
    ● 𝐌𝐀𝐏_𝐊𝐄𝐘𝐒: [addr] → [arr_addr] – array of all keys
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  .sym m                                                                │
  │ 2:  │  ; Create map                                                          │
  │ 3:  │  MAP_NEW                                                               │
  │ 4:  │  PUSH_CONST 0                                                          │
  │ 5:  │  BIND                                                                  │
  │ 6:  │  ; Set map[1] = 100                                                    │
  │ 7:  │  PUSH_CONST 0                                                          │
  │ 8:  │  LOOKUP                                                                │
  │ 9:  │  PUSH_INT 1                                                            │
  │ 10: │  PUSH_INT 100                                                          │
  │ 11: │  MAP_SET                                                               │
  │ 12: │  ; Set map[2] = 200                                                    │
  │ 13: │  PUSH_CONST 0                                                          │
  │ 14: │  LOOKUP                                                                │
  │ 15: │  PUSH_INT 2                                                            │
  │ 16: │  PUSH_INT 200                                                          │
  │ 17: │  MAP_SET                                                               │
  │ 18: │  ; Get map[1]                                                          │
  │ 19: │  PUSH_CONST 0                                                          │
  │ 20: │  LOOKUP                                                                │
  │ 21: │  PUSH_INT 1                                                            │
  │ 22: │  MAP_GET                                                               │
  │ 23: │  OUTPUT                                                                │
  │ 24: │  HALT                                                                  │
  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
     ╭─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
  ╭──┴────────────╮                                                            │
  │ 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output │|··························································|│
  ╰──┬────────────╯                                                            │
     │   100                                                                  ░│
     ╰─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯
  
  We create a map, store two entries, and retrieve the value at key 1.
  
  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ 1:  │  ; Check map length                                                    │
  │ 2:  │  .sym m                                                                │
  │ 3:  │  MAP_NEW                                                               │
  │ 4:  │  PUSH_CONST 0                                                          │
  │ 5:  │  BIND                                                                  │
  │ 6:  │  ; Add 3 entries                                                       │
  │ 7:  │  PUSH_CONST 0                                                          │
  │ 8:  │  LOOKUP                                                                │
  │ 9:  │  PUSH_INT 1                                                            │
  │ 10: │  PUSH_INT 10                                                           │
  │ 11: │  MAP_SET                                                               │
  │ 12: │  PUSH_CONST 0                                                          │
  │ 13: │  LOOKUP                                                                │
