  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
     ╭─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
  ╭──┴────────────╮                                                            │
  │ 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες Output │|··························································|│
  ╰──┬────────────╯                                                            │
     │   55                                                                   ░│
     ╰─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯
  
  The  loop runs for  i=2..10 (nine  iterations). Starting from  fib(0)=0 and  fi-
  b(1)=1, we accumulate up to fib(10)=55.
  
  
  𝐎𝐩𝐜𝐨𝐝𝐞 𝐑𝐞𝐟𝐞𝐫𝐞𝐧𝐜𝐞
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  Complete  reference of every Subnivean  instruction. Stack effects use the nota-
  tion [popped] → [pushed].  Operand column shows what the operand means (– if no-
  ne).
  
                                  Stack Operations
                                o══════════════════o
    ● 𝐍𝐎𝐏: no operation
    ● 𝐏𝐎𝐏: [a] → [] – discard top of stack
    ● 𝐃𝐔𝐏: [a] → [a, a] – duplicate top
    ● 𝐒𝐖𝐀𝐏: [a, b] → [b, a] – swap top two
    ● 𝐑𝐎𝐓: [a, b, c] → [b, c, a] – rotate top three
                                     Constants
                                   o═══════════o
    ● 𝐏𝐔𝐒𝐇_𝐍𝐈𝐋: [] → [nil]
    ● 𝐏𝐔𝐒𝐇_𝐓𝐑𝐔𝐄: [] → [1]
    ● 𝐏𝐔𝐒𝐇_𝐅𝐀𝐋𝐒𝐄: [] → [0]
    ● 𝐏𝐔𝐒𝐇_𝐈𝐍𝐓 𝐧: [] → [n] – push immediate integer
    ● 𝐏𝐔𝐒𝐇_𝐂𝐎𝐍𝐒𝐓 𝐧: [] → [pool[n]] – push from constant pool
                                  Scope Operations
                                o══════════════════o
    ● 𝐒𝐂𝐎𝐏𝐄_𝐍𝐄𝐖: create child scope, enter it
    ● 𝐒𝐂𝐎𝐏𝐄_𝐏𝐎𝐏: exit to parent scope
    ● 𝐒𝐂𝐎𝐏𝐄_𝐂𝐀𝐏𝐓𝐔𝐑𝐄: [] → [scope] – push current scope
    ● 𝐒𝐂𝐎𝐏𝐄_𝐑𝐄𝐒𝐓𝐎𝐑𝐄: [scope] → [] – restore scope
                                 Bindings (Static)
                               o═══════════════════o
    ● 𝐁𝐈𝐍𝐃: [value, sym] → [] – bind in current scope
    ● 𝐋𝐎𝐎𝐊𝐔𝐏: [sym] → [value] – search scope chain
    ● 𝐋𝐎𝐎𝐊𝐔𝐏_𝐇𝐄𝐑𝐄: [sym] → [value] – current scope only
    ● 𝐒𝐄𝐓: [value, sym] → [] – update existing binding
                                 Bindings (Dynamic)
                               o════════════════════o
    ● 𝐁𝐈𝐍𝐃_𝐃𝐘𝐍: [value, str] → [] – intern string, bind
    ● 𝐋𝐎𝐎𝐊𝐔𝐏_𝐃𝐘𝐍: [str] → [value] – intern string, lookup
    ● 𝐒𝐄𝐓_𝐃𝐘𝐍: [value, str] → [] – intern string, set
                                       Cells
                                     o═══════o
    ● 𝐂𝐄𝐋𝐋_𝐍𝐄𝐖: [value] → [cell] – box the value
    ● 𝐂𝐄𝐋𝐋_𝐆𝐄𝐓: [cell] → [value] – unbox
    ● 𝐂𝐄𝐋𝐋_𝐒𝐄𝐓: [value, cell] → [] – mutate contents
    ● 𝐂𝐄𝐋𝐋_𝐈𝐍𝐂: [cell] → [new_val] – increment integer in cell
    ● 𝐂𝐄𝐋𝐋_𝐃𝐄𝐂: [cell] → [new_val] – decrement integer in cell
                                     Arithmetic
                                   o════════════o
    ● 𝐀𝐃𝐃: [b, a] → [a+b]
    ● 𝐒𝐔𝐁: [b, a] → [a-b]
    ● 𝐌𝐔𝐋: [b, a] → [a*b]
    ● 𝐃𝐈𝐕: [b, a] → [a/b]
    ● 𝐌𝐎𝐃: [b, a] → [a mod b]
    ● 𝐍𝐄𝐆: [a] → [-a]
    ● 𝐑𝐀𝐍𝐃: [max] → [random 0..max-1]
                                     Comparison
                                   o════════════o
    ● 𝐄𝐐: [b, a] → [a==b ? 1 : 0]
    ● 𝐍𝐄: [b, a] → [a!=b ? 1 : 0]
    ● 𝐋𝐓: [b, a] → [a<b ? 1 : 0]
    ● 𝐆𝐓: [b, a] → [a>b ? 1 : 0]
    ● 𝐋𝐄: [b, a] → [a<=b ? 1 : 0]
    ● 𝐆𝐄: [b, a] → [a>=b ? 1 : 0]
                                       Logic
                                     o═══════o
    ● 𝐀𝐍𝐃: [b, a] → [a&&b ? 1 : 0]
    ● 𝐎𝐑: [b, a] → [a||b ? 1 : 0]
    ● 𝐍𝐎𝐓: [a] → [!a ? 1 : 0]
                                    Control Flow
                                  o══════════════o
    ● 𝐉𝐔𝐌𝐏 𝐥𝐚𝐛𝐞𝐥: unconditional jump
    ● 𝐉𝐔𝐌𝐏_𝐈𝐅 𝐥𝐚𝐛𝐞𝐥: [cond] → [] – jump if truthy
    ● 𝐉𝐔𝐌𝐏_𝐔𝐍𝐋𝐄𝐒𝐒 𝐥𝐚𝐛𝐞𝐥: [cond] → [] – jump if falsy
    ● 𝐋𝐎𝐎𝐏 𝐥𝐚𝐛𝐞𝐥: backward jump
                                     Functions
                                   o═══════════o
    ● 𝐂𝐋𝐎𝐒𝐔𝐑𝐄 𝐧: [scope] → [closure] – wrap function pool[n]
    ● 𝐂𝐀𝐋𝐋 𝐧: [args…, closure] → [result] – call with n args
    ● 𝐓𝐀𝐈𝐋_𝐂𝐀𝐋𝐋 𝐧: like CALL, reuses frame
    ● 𝐈𝐍𝐕𝐎𝐊𝐄_𝐃𝐘𝐍 𝐧: [args…, val] → [result] – dynamic dispatch
    ● 𝐑𝐄𝐓𝐔𝐑𝐍: return nil
    ● 𝐑𝐄𝐓𝐔𝐑𝐍_𝐕𝐀𝐋: [value] → ; return TOS
                                       Arrays
                                     o════════o
    ● 𝐀𝐑𝐑𝐀𝐘_𝐍𝐄𝐖 𝐧: [elems…] → [arr] – n = element count
    ● 𝐀𝐑𝐑𝐀𝐘_𝐆𝐄𝐓: [idx, arr] → [elem]
    ● 𝐀𝐑𝐑𝐀𝐘_𝐒𝐄𝐓: [val, idx, arr] → []
    ● 𝐀𝐑𝐑𝐀𝐘_𝐋𝐄𝐍: [arr] → [len]
    ● 𝐀𝐑𝐑𝐀𝐘_𝐏𝐔𝐒𝐇: [val, arr] → []
    ● 𝐀𝐑𝐑𝐀𝐘_𝐏𝐎𝐏: [arr] → [val]
                                        Maps
                                      o══════o
    ● 𝐌𝐀𝐏_𝐍𝐄𝐖: [] → [addr]
    ● 𝐌𝐀𝐏_𝐆𝐄𝐓: [key, addr] → [value]
    ● 𝐌𝐀𝐏_𝐒𝐄𝐓: [val, key, addr] → []
    ● 𝐌𝐀𝐏_𝐇𝐀𝐒: [key, addr] → [0/1]
    ● 𝐌𝐀𝐏_𝐃𝐄𝐋: [key, addr] → [0/1]
    ● 𝐌𝐀𝐏_𝐋𝐄𝐍: [addr] → [count]
    ● 𝐌𝐀𝐏_𝐊𝐄𝐘𝐒: [addr] → [arr_addr]
                                    Heap Memory
                                  o═════════════o
    ● 𝐌𝐄𝐌_𝐀𝐋𝐋𝐎𝐂: [count] → [addr]
    ● 𝐌𝐄𝐌_𝐒𝐓𝐎𝐑𝐄: [val, idx, addr] → []
    ● 𝐌𝐄𝐌_𝐋𝐎𝐀𝐃: [idx, addr] → [value]
    ● 𝐌𝐄𝐌_𝐋𝐄𝐍: [addr] → [len]
                                      Strings
                                    o═════════o
    ● 𝐂𝐎𝐍𝐂𝐀𝐓: [b, a] → [a+b] – string concatenation
    ● 𝐒𝐓𝐑𝐈𝐍𝐆𝐈𝐅𝐘: [val] → [str] – convert to string
    ● 𝐒𝐘𝐌𝐁𝐎𝐋: [str] → [sym] – intern string as symbol
                                       Output
                                     o════════o
    ● 𝐎𝐔𝐓𝐏𝐔𝐓: [val] → [] – stringify and append to output
    ● 𝐎𝐔𝐓𝐏𝐔𝐓_𝐑𝐀𝐖 𝐧: emit literal text from pool[n]
    ● 𝐄𝐌𝐈𝐓_𝐂𝐔𝐑𝐒𝐎𝐑: [row, col] → [] – emit cursor positioning escape
                                      Special
                                    o═════════o
    ● 𝐇𝐀𝐋𝐓: stop execution
    ● 𝐁𝐑𝐄𝐀𝐊𝐏𝐎𝐈𝐍𝐓: debugger hook
    ● 𝐀𝐒𝐒𝐄𝐑𝐓: [cond, msg] → [] – error if falsy
    ● 𝐋𝐄𝐍: [val] → [len] – unified length
                                Assembler Directives
                              o══════════════════════o
    ● .𝐜𝐨𝐧𝐬𝐭 “𝐭𝐞𝐱𝐭”: add a string to the constant pool
    ● .𝐬𝐲𝐦 𝐧𝐚𝐦𝐞: intern a symbol, add to the constant pool
    ● 𝐧𝐚𝐦𝐞:: define a label (jump target)
    ● ; 𝐭𝐞𝐱𝐭: comment (ignored)
  
  Both .const and .sym share the same  constant pool. Indices are  assigned seque-
  ntially:  the first  directive is index 0, the  second is index 1, regardless of
  type. Blank lines are ignored.
  
                                 Instruction Format
                               o════════════════════o
  
  Each  instruction is 8 bytes: a 4-byte  opcode and a 4-byte signed  operand. The
  operand  is  an immediate  integer, a constant  pool  index, or a relative  jump
  offset  depending on the  instruction. The assembler handles all offset computa-
  tion automatically.

@label subnivean_guide
    The CL guide teaches how to write Computational Lambdas -- the high-level
    language compiled by Hyades.  This companion guide goes one level deeper.
    Here you will learn what CL compiles \textit{down to}: the raw bytecode
    executed by the Subnivean virtual machine.

    Every example in this guide is \textit{live}.  The boxed assembly listings
    are not pseudocode; they are real programs executed by \cmd{sn}\{...\},
    Hyades' inline assembler.  Each one runs inside the typesetting engine and
    produces the output you see beside it.

    Subnivean is a \textit{stack machine}.  There are no registers.  Every
    value lives on a stack; instructions pop their operands and push their
    results.  If you have ever used an HP calculator in RPN mode, or written
    Forth, the model will feel familiar.  If not, the first few sections will
    build the intuition from scratch.

    Why does Subnivean exist?  Speed.  The text-based macro interpreter
    expands strings character by character -- fine for formatting, but far
    too slow for Game of Life or Matrix Digital Rain at interactive frame
    rates.  Subnivean compiles to bytecode and executes it in a tight C
    loop, achieving a 65x speedup over interpreted CL.

    The \cmd{sn}\{...\} command feeds source text to a two-pass assembler.
    Pass one collects labels and constant-pool directives.  Pass two emits
    instructions.  The resulting bytecode is handed to the VM, which executes
    it and returns whatever was sent to OUTPUT as a string.

    The sections build on each other.  By the end you will have written a
    complete GCD algorithm and an iterative Fibonacci generator at the
    bytecode level -- and you will know exactly what every instruction does.


    \section{\textbf{The Stack}}

    Everything in Subnivean begins with the stack.  PUSH\_INT places an
    integer on top; OUTPUT pops the top value and sends it to the output
    stream.  HALT stops execution.

    \hylst{\verb|
PUSH_INT 42
OUTPUT
HALT
|}{%
    \indented{
        \sn{
PUSH_INT 42
OUTPUT
HALT
        }
    }
}

    That is a complete program.  PUSH\_INT 42 pushes the integer 42 onto
    the stack.  OUTPUT pops it, converts it to its string representation,
    and appends it to the output buffer.  HALT stops the VM.

    Instructions consume their operands by popping.  After OUTPUT, the
    stack is empty again.  Let us try arithmetic:

    \hylst{\verb|
PUSH_INT 5
PUSH_INT 3
ADD
OUTPUT
HALT
|}{%
    \indented{
        \sn{
PUSH_INT 5
PUSH_INT 3
ADD
OUTPUT
HALT
        }
    }
}

    PUSH\_INT 5 pushes 5.  PUSH\_INT 3 pushes 3.  Now the stack holds
    [5, 3] (3 on top).  ADD pops both and pushes their sum: [8].  OUTPUT
    pops 8 and prints it.

    \fculn{DUP and POP}

    DUP duplicates the top of stack.  POP discards it.

    \hylst{\verb|
PUSH_INT 10
DUP
ADD
OUTPUT
HALT
|}{%
    \indented{
        \sn{
PUSH_INT 10
DUP
ADD
OUTPUT
HALT
        }
    }
}

    DUP copies 10, giving [10, 10].  ADD produces [20].

    \fculn{SWAP and ROT}

    SWAP exchanges the top two elements.  ROT rotates the top three:
    [a, b, c] becomes [b, c, a].

    Order matters for non-commutative operations.  SUB pops [b, a] and
    computes a - b.  If you push 10 then 3, you get 10 - 3 = 7:

    \hylst{\verb|
PUSH_INT 10
PUSH_INT 3
SUB
OUTPUT
HALT
|}{%
    \indented{
        \sn{
PUSH_INT 10
PUSH_INT 3
SUB
OUTPUT
HALT
        }
    }
}

    But if you need 3 - 10, push them in the opposite order -- or use
    SWAP after pushing:

    \hylst{\verb|
PUSH_INT 10
PUSH_INT 3
SWAP
SUB
OUTPUT
HALT
|}{%
    \indented{
        \sn{
PUSH_INT 10
PUSH_INT 3
SWAP
SUB
OUTPUT
HALT
        }
    }
}

    \fculn{Special Values}

    PUSH\_NIL pushes a nil value.  PUSH\_TRUE pushes integer 1.
    PUSH\_FALSE pushes integer 0.  Booleans in Subnivean are just
    integers: any nonzero value is truthy, zero is falsy.

    \hylst{\verb|
PUSH_TRUE
PUSH_FALSE
ADD
OUTPUT
HALT
|}{%
    \indented{
        \sn{
PUSH_TRUE
PUSH_FALSE
ADD
OUTPUT
HALT
        }
    }
}

    True (1) plus false (0) equals 1.

    \begin{didyouknow}
    \center{STACK DEPTH}
    The Subnivean stack is 4096 entries deep -- more than enough for any
    computation.  A stack overflow halts the VM with an error.
    \end{didyouknow}


    {}\\
    \section{\textbf{Arithmetic}}

    Subnivean provides six arithmetic operations.  All binary operators
    pop two values [b, a] and push the result.  The \textit{first} value
    pushed is the left operand:

    \indented{\fancylist{
        - \textbf{ADD}: a + b
        - \textbf{SUB}: a - b
        - \textbf{MUL}: a * b
        - \textbf{DIV}: a / b (integer, truncates toward zero)
        - \textbf{MOD}: a mod b (remainder)
        - \textbf{NEG}: unary negation (one operand)
    }}

    \hylst{\verb|
; Multiplication: 6 * 7 = 42
PUSH_INT 6
PUSH_INT 7
MUL
OUTPUT
HALT
|}{%
    \indented{
        \sn{
PUSH_INT 6
PUSH_INT 7
MUL
OUTPUT
HALT
        }
    }
}

    \hylst{\verb|
; Division: 20 / 3 = 6 (truncated)
PUSH_INT 20
PUSH_INT 3
DIV
OUTPUT
HALT
|}{%
    \indented{
        \sn{
PUSH_INT 20
PUSH_INT 3
DIV
OUTPUT
HALT
        }
    }
}

    \hylst{\verb|
; Modulo: 17 mod 5 = 2
PUSH_INT 17
PUSH_INT 5
MOD
OUTPUT
HALT
|}{%
    \indented{
        \sn{
PUSH_INT 17
PUSH_INT 5
MOD
OUTPUT
HALT
        }
    }
}

    NEG takes a single operand and negates it:

    \hylst{\verb|
PUSH_INT 42
NEG
OUTPUT
HALT
|}{%
    \indented{
        \sn{
PUSH_INT 42
NEG
OUTPUT
HALT
        }
    }
}

    \begin{didyouknow}
    \center{INTEGER PRECISION}
    All values are 64-bit signed integers.  Integer division truncates
    toward zero.  There are no floating-point numbers in Subnivean.
    \end{didyouknow}


    {}\\
    \section{\textbf{Constants and Strings}}

    Integers are pushed with PUSH\_INT.  But what about strings?  Strings
    live in the \textit{constant pool} -- a per-function array of compile-
    time values.  The assembler directive \textbf{.const} adds a string:

    \fancylisting{\verb|
.const "hello"       ; index 0
.const "world"       ; index 1
PUSH_CONST 0         ; push "hello"
PUSH_CONST 1         ; push "world"
|}

    The first .const gets index 0, the second gets index 1, and so on.
    PUSH\_CONST loads from the constant pool by index.

    \hylst{\verb|
.const "hello"
PUSH_CONST 0
OUTPUT
HALT
|}{%
    \indented{
        \sn{
.const "hello"
PUSH_CONST 0
OUTPUT
HALT
        }
    }
}

    \fculn{String Concatenation}

    CONCAT pops two strings [b, a] and pushes their concatenation a+b:

    \hylst{\verb|
.const "hello "
.const "world"
PUSH_CONST 0
PUSH_CONST 1
CONCAT
OUTPUT
HALT
|}{%
    \indented{
        \sn{
.const "hello "
.const "world"
PUSH_CONST 0
PUSH_CONST 1
CONCAT
OUTPUT
HALT
        }
    }
}

    \fculn{STRINGIFY}

    STRINGIFY converts any value to its string representation.  This is
    how you mix integers and strings:

    \hylst{\verb|
.const " is the answer"
PUSH_INT 42
STRINGIFY
PUSH_CONST 0
CONCAT
OUTPUT
HALT
|}{%
    \indented{
        \sn{
.const " is the answer"
PUSH_INT 42
STRINGIFY
PUSH_CONST 0
CONCAT
OUTPUT
HALT
        }
    }
}

    \fculn{Escape Sequences}

    Strings in .const support standard escape sequences:

    \indented{\fancylist{
        - \verb|\\n| -- newline
        - \verb|\\t| -- tab
        - \verb|\\\\| -- literal backslash
        - \verb|\\"| -- literal double quote
    }}

    \fculn{Constant Pool Indexing}

    Pool indices are assigned sequentially.  Both .const and .sym (covered
    next) share the same pool.  The first directive is index 0, the second
    is index 1, regardless of whether it is .const or .sym.  Plan your
    indices accordingly.

    \begin{didyouknow}
    \center{OUTPUT ACCEPTS ANYTHING}
    OUTPUT calls STRINGIFY internally.  You can OUTPUT an integer
    directly without explicit STRINGIFY -- it will be converted
    automatically.  STRINGIFY is needed when you want to CONCAT an
    integer with a string.
    \end{didyouknow}


    {}\\
    \section{\textbf{Symbols and Bindings}}

    Variables in Subnivean are \textit{bindings}: a symbol (the name)
    associated with a value in a \textit{scope}.  The assembler provides
    the .sym directive to intern a symbol:

    \fancylisting{\verb|
.sym x          ; intern symbol "x", add to constant pool
|}

    Like .const, .sym occupies a constant pool slot.  The difference is
    that .sym creates an interned \textit{symbol} -- a unique identity
    used for fast variable lookup.

    Three instructions work with bindings:

    \indented{\fancylist{
        - \textbf{BIND}: [value, sym] → [] -- bind value to symbol in current scope
        - \textbf{LOOKUP}: [sym] → [value] -- search scope chain for symbol
        - \textbf{SET}: [value, sym] → [] -- update existing binding in chain
    }}

    \hylst{\verb|
.sym x
PUSH_INT 42
PUSH_CONST 0
BIND
PUSH_CONST 0
LOOKUP
OUTPUT
HALT
|}{%
    \indented{
        \sn{
.sym x
PUSH_INT 42
PUSH_CONST 0
BIND
PUSH_CONST 0
LOOKUP
OUTPUT
HALT
        }
    }
}

    Step by step: .sym x interns "x" at pool index 0.  PUSH\_INT 42
    pushes the value.  PUSH\_CONST 0 pushes the symbol.  BIND pops both
    and stores the binding x=42 in the current scope.  Then PUSH\_CONST 0
    pushes the symbol again, LOOKUP finds it, and OUTPUT prints 42.

    SET updates an existing binding without creating a new one:

    \hylst{\verb|
.sym x
PUSH_INT 10
PUSH_CONST 0
BIND
PUSH_INT 99
PUSH_CONST 0
SET
PUSH_CONST 0
LOOKUP
OUTPUT
HALT
|}{%
    \indented{
        \sn{
.sym x
PUSH_INT 10
PUSH_CONST 0
BIND
PUSH_INT 99
PUSH_CONST 0
SET
PUSH_CONST 0
LOOKUP
OUTPUT
HALT
        }
    }
}

    First x is bound to 10, then SET overwrites it with 99.

    \begin{didyouknow}
    \center{WHY SYMBOLS?}
    Symbols are \textit{interned} -- each unique name exists exactly once
    in memory.  Comparing two symbols is a pointer comparison (O(1)),
    not a string comparison (O(n)).  This is why variable lookup is fast.
    \end{didyouknow}


    {}\\
    \section{\textbf{Cells -- Mutable Boxes}}

    Subnivean values are immutable.  An integer on the stack is just a
    number -- you cannot increment it in place.  But programs need mutable
    state.  The solution is \textit{cells}: mutable boxes that wrap a
    value.

    \indented{\fancylist{
        - \textbf{CELL\_NEW}: [value] → [cell] -- box the value
        - \textbf{CELL\_GET}: [cell] → [value] -- unbox (copy the contents)
        - \textbf{CELL\_SET}: [value, cell] → [] -- mutate the contents
        - \textbf{CELL\_INC}: [cell] → [new\_val] -- increment integer in cell, push new value
        - \textbf{CELL\_DEC}: [cell] → [new\_val] -- decrement integer in cell, push new value
    }}

    The canonical pattern for a mutable variable:

    \fancylisting{\verb|
; Create mutable variable x = 5
.sym x
PUSH_INT 5          ; value
CELL_NEW            ; wrap in cell
PUSH_CONST 0        ; symbol
BIND                ; bind cell to symbol
|}

    To read the variable, look up the cell, then CELL\_GET.  To mutate
    it, look up the cell, then CELL\_SET (or CELL\_INC/CELL\_DEC):

    \hylst{\verb|
.sym x
PUSH_INT 5
CELL_NEW
PUSH_CONST 0
BIND
; read x
PUSH_CONST 0
LOOKUP
CELL_GET
OUTPUT
HALT
|}{%
    \indented{
        \sn{
.sym x
PUSH_INT 5
CELL_NEW
PUSH_CONST 0
BIND
PUSH_CONST 0
LOOKUP
CELL_GET
OUTPUT
HALT
        }
    }
}

    CELL\_INC increments the integer inside a cell and pushes the new
    value.  Here we increment x five times:

    \hylst{\verb|
.sym x
PUSH_INT 0
CELL_NEW
PUSH_CONST 0
BIND
; increment 5 times
PUSH_CONST 0
LOOKUP
CELL_INC
POP
PUSH_CONST 0
LOOKUP
CELL_INC
POP
PUSH_CONST 0
LOOKUP
CELL_INC
POP
PUSH_CONST 0
LOOKUP
CELL_INC
POP
PUSH_CONST 0
LOOKUP
CELL_INC
OUTPUT
HALT
|}{%
    \indented{
        \sn{
.sym x
PUSH_INT 0
CELL_NEW
PUSH_CONST 0
BIND
PUSH_CONST 0
LOOKUP
CELL_INC
POP
PUSH_CONST 0
LOOKUP
CELL_INC
POP
PUSH_CONST 0
LOOKUP
CELL_INC
POP
PUSH_CONST 0
LOOKUP
CELL_INC
POP
PUSH_CONST 0
LOOKUP
CELL_INC
OUTPUT
HALT
        }
    }
}

    We start at 0 and increment five times; the final CELL\_INC pushes 5,
    which OUTPUT prints.  Each intermediate CELL\_INC result is discarded
    with POP.

    \begin{didyouknow}
    \center{CELLS AND CL}
    In CL, \cmd{let}\<x:int\>\{5\} compiles to exactly: PUSH\_INT 5 /
    CELL\_NEW / PUSH\_CONST \<sym\_x\> / BIND.  Every mutable variable
    is a cell.  Reading \$\{x\} compiles to LOOKUP / CELL\_GET.
    \end{didyouknow}


    {}\\
    \section{\textbf{Comparison and Logic}}

    Subnivean provides six comparison operators and three logic operators.
    All comparisons pop [b, a] and push 1 (true) or 0 (false):

    \indented{\fancylist{
        - \textbf{EQ}: a == b
        - \textbf{NE}: a != b
        - \textbf{LT}: a < b
        - \textbf{GT}: a > b
        - \textbf{LE}: a <= b
        - \textbf{GE}: a >= b
    }}

    Logic operators:

    \indented{\fancylist{
        - \textbf{AND}: a \&\& b (non-short-circuit)
        - \textbf{OR}: a || b
        - \textbf{NOT}: !a (unary)
    }}

    Results are plain integers.  1 is true, 0 is false:

    \hylst{\verb|
; 10 < 20?
PUSH_INT 10
PUSH_INT 20
LT
OUTPUT
HALT
|}{%
    \indented{
        \sn{
PUSH_INT 10
PUSH_INT 20
LT
OUTPUT
HALT
        }
    }
}

    \hylst{\verb|
; 5 == 5?
PUSH_INT 5
PUSH_INT 5
EQ
OUTPUT
HALT
|}{%
    \indented{
        \sn{
PUSH_INT 5
PUSH_INT 5
EQ
OUTPUT
HALT
        }
    }
}

    \hylst{\verb|
; NOT 0 = 1
PUSH_FALSE
NOT
OUTPUT
HALT
|}{%
    \indented{
        \sn{
PUSH_FALSE
NOT
OUTPUT
HALT
        }
    }
}

    These are the building blocks for control flow, which follows next.


    {}\\
    \section{\textbf{Control Flow}}

    Without jumps, programs execute top to bottom.  Labels and jump
    instructions add branching and loops.

    \fculn{Labels}

    A label is an identifier followed by a colon.  It marks a position
    in the instruction stream:

    \fancylisting{\verb|
start:                ; defines label "start"
    PUSH_INT 1
done:                 ; defines label "done"
    HALT
|}

    Labels do not emit instructions -- they are resolved by the assembler
    and converted to relative offsets.

    \fculn{Jump Instructions}

    \indented{\fancylist{
        - \textbf{JUMP label}: unconditional jump
        - \textbf{JUMP\_IF label}: [cond] → [] -- jump if truthy (nonzero)
        - \textbf{JUMP\_UNLESS label}: [cond] → [] -- jump if falsy (zero)
        - \textbf{LOOP label}: backward jump (for loops)
    }}

    \fculn{If/Else Pattern}

    The classic conditional: test a condition, jump to one branch or
    the other.

    \hylst{\verb|
.const "yes"
.const "no"
; Is 10 > 5?
PUSH_INT 10
PUSH_INT 5
GT
JUMP_IF yes
; false branch
PUSH_CONST 1
JUMP end
yes:
PUSH_CONST 0
end:
OUTPUT
HALT
|}{%
    \indented{
        \sn{
.const "yes"
.const "no"
PUSH_INT 10
PUSH_INT 5
GT
JUMP_IF yes
PUSH_CONST 1
JUMP end
yes:
PUSH_CONST 0
end:
OUTPUT
HALT
        }
    }
}

    GT pushes 1 (10 > 5 is true).  JUMP\_IF pops it and jumps to
    \textit{yes}.  The string "yes" is pushed and printed.

    \fculn{A Simple Countdown Loop}

    Loops use LOOP for backward jumps.  Here is a countdown from 5 to 1:

    \hylst{\verb|
.sym n
.const " "
; n = 5 (as cell)
PUSH_INT 5
CELL_NEW
PUSH_CONST 0
BIND
loop:
  ; output n
  PUSH_CONST 0
  LOOKUP
  CELL_GET
  OUTPUT
  ; output space
  PUSH_CONST 1
  OUTPUT
  ; decrement n
  PUSH_CONST 0
  LOOKUP
  CELL_DEC
  ; if n > 0, continue
  PUSH_INT 0
  GT
  JUMP_IF loop
HALT
|}{%
    \indented{
        \sn{
.sym n
.const " "
PUSH_INT 5
CELL_NEW
PUSH_CONST 0
BIND
loop:
PUSH_CONST 0
LOOKUP
CELL_GET
OUTPUT
PUSH_CONST 1
OUTPUT
PUSH_CONST 0
LOOKUP
CELL_DEC
PUSH_INT 0
GT
JUMP_IF loop
HALT
        }
    }
}

    CELL\_DEC decrements the cell and pushes the new value.  We compare
    that with 0 using GT.  If still positive, JUMP\_IF loops back.

    \fculn{Sum 1 to 10}

    A slightly more involved loop that computes 1+2+...+10 = 55:

    \hylst{\verb|
.sym sum
.sym i
; sum = 0
PUSH_INT 0
CELL_NEW
PUSH_CONST 0
BIND
; i = 1
PUSH_INT 1
CELL_NEW
PUSH_CONST 1
BIND
loop:
  ; sum += i
  PUSH_CONST 1
  LOOKUP
  CELL_GET
  PUSH_CONST 0
  LOOKUP
  CELL_GET
  ADD
  PUSH_CONST 0
  LOOKUP
  CELL_SET
  ; i++
  PUSH_CONST 1
  LOOKUP
  CELL_INC
  ; if i <= 10, loop
  PUSH_INT 10
  LE
  JUMP_IF loop
; output sum
PUSH_CONST 0
LOOKUP
CELL_GET
OUTPUT
HALT
|}{%
    \indented{
        \sn{
.sym sum
.sym i
PUSH_INT 0
CELL_NEW
PUSH_CONST 0
BIND
PUSH_INT 1
CELL_NEW
PUSH_CONST 1
BIND
loop:
PUSH_CONST 1
LOOKUP
CELL_GET
PUSH_CONST 0
LOOKUP
CELL_GET
ADD
PUSH_CONST 0
LOOKUP
CELL_SET
PUSH_CONST 1
LOOKUP
CELL_INC
PUSH_INT 10
LE
JUMP_IF loop
PUSH_CONST 0
LOOKUP
CELL_GET
OUTPUT
HALT
        }
    }
}

    \fculn{The Two Loop Patterns}

    \textit{Bottom-tested} (do-while): the body always executes at least
    once.  The condition comes after the body:

    \fancylisting{\verb|
loop:
    ; ... body ...
    ; ... condition ...
    JUMP_IF loop         ; repeat while true
|}

    \textit{Top-tested} (while): the condition is checked before the body.
    If false initially, the body never executes:

    \fancylisting{\verb|
loop:
    ; ... condition ...
    JUMP_UNLESS done     ; exit if false
    ; ... body ...
    JUMP loop
done:
|}

    \begin{didyouknow}
    \center{LABELS AND OFFSETS}
    JUMP, JUMP\_IF, and JUMP\_UNLESS use \textit{relative} offsets
    internally, but the assembler computes them from label names.  You
    never need to count instructions by hand.  Forward references work
    -- you can JUMP\_IF done before done: is defined.
    \end{didyouknow}


    {}\\
    \section{\textbf{Scopes}}

    Subnivean organizes bindings into a \textit{scope chain}.  Each scope
    has a parent; LOOKUP searches up the chain.

    \indented{\fancylist{
        - \textbf{SCOPE\_NEW}: create a child scope of the current one, enter it
        - \textbf{SCOPE\_POP}: exit to parent (child freed if no references remain)
        - \textbf{SCOPE\_CAPTURE}: push the current scope as a value
        - \textbf{SCOPE\_RESTORE}: pop a scope value, make it current
    }}

    Scopes let you shadow variables without losing the outer binding:

    \hylst{\verb|
.sym x
.const " "
; x = 10 in outer scope
PUSH_INT 10
PUSH_CONST 0
BIND
; enter new scope
SCOPE_NEW
; x = 99 in inner scope (shadows outer)
PUSH_INT 99
PUSH_CONST 0
BIND
; read inner x
PUSH_CONST 0
LOOKUP
OUTPUT
PUSH_CONST 1
OUTPUT
; exit inner scope
SCOPE_POP
; read outer x (still 10)
PUSH_CONST 0
LOOKUP
OUTPUT
HALT
|}{%
    \indented{
        \sn{
.sym x
.const " "
PUSH_INT 10
PUSH_CONST 0
BIND
SCOPE_NEW
PUSH_INT 99
PUSH_CONST 0
BIND
PUSH_CONST 0
LOOKUP
OUTPUT
PUSH_CONST 1
OUTPUT
SCOPE_POP
PUSH_CONST 0
LOOKUP
OUTPUT
HALT
        }
    }
}

    The inner scope binds x=99, which shadows the outer x=10.  After
    SCOPE\_POP, the inner scope is destroyed and x resolves to 10 again.

    \begin{didyouknow}
    \center{WHY SCOPES MATTER}
    Closures capture scopes.  In CL loops, per-iteration scopes give
    each closure its own variables -- the "JavaScript let in for-loop"
    semantics that prevent the classic "all closures share one counter"
    bug.
    \end{didyouknow}


    {}\\
    \section{\textbf{Functions and Closures}}

    Subnivean supports first-class closures: a function paired with the
    scope in which it was created.

    \indented{\fancylist{
        - \textbf{CLOSURE}: [scope] → [closure] -- wraps a function (by constant pool index) with a captured scope
        - \textbf{CALL}: [args..., closure] → [result] -- call with operand = argc
        - \textbf{RETURN}: return nil from current function
        - \textbf{RETURN\_VAL}: [value] → ; return TOS
        - \textbf{TAIL\_CALL}: like CALL but reuses the stack frame (optimization)
    }}

    Creating a closure requires a compiled sub-function stored in the
    constant pool.  The \cmd{sn}\{\} assembler compiles a single flat
    function, so closures cannot be demonstrated in raw assembly.
    However, the mechanism is straightforward:

    \fancylisting{\verb|
; How CL compiles a closure:
; 1. The lambda body is compiled to a Function
;    and stored in the constant pool at some index N
; 2. At the call site:
SCOPE_CAPTURE        ; push current scope
CLOSURE N            ; wrap function N with scope -> closure
CALL 0               ; call with 0 arguments
|}

    When CALL executes, the VM creates a new call frame, pushes arguments
    into a child scope of the captured scope, and transfers control.
    RETURN\_VAL pops the result and passes it back to the caller.

    \begin{didyouknow}
    \center{COMPILATION PATTERN}
    Every \#\{...\} lambda body compiles to a Function stored in the
    parent's constant pool.  \cmd{invoke} emits SCOPE\_CAPTURE /
    PUSH\_CONST / CLOSURE / CALL.  Arguments are pushed before the
    closure, and the CALL operand indicates how many there are.
    \end{didyouknow}


    {}\\
    \section{\textbf{Arrays}}

    Subnivean arrays live in a persistent store and are accessed by
    address.

    \indented{\fancylist{
        - \textbf{ARRAY\_NEW}: [elems...] → [array] -- operand = element count
        - \textbf{ARRAY\_GET}: [idx, arr] → [elem]
        - \textbf{ARRAY\_SET}: [val, idx, arr] → []
        - \textbf{ARRAY\_LEN}: [arr] → [len]
        - \textbf{ARRAY\_PUSH}: [val, arr] → []
        - \textbf{ARRAY\_POP}: [arr] → [val]
    }}

    Create an array with three elements and read the second one (index 1):

    \hylst{\verb|
; Create array [10, 20, 30]
PUSH_INT 10
PUSH_INT 20
PUSH_INT 30
ARRAY_NEW 3
; Read element at index 1
DUP
PUSH_INT 1
ARRAY_GET
OUTPUT
HALT
|}{%
    \indented{
        \sn{
PUSH_INT 10
PUSH_INT 20
PUSH_INT 30
ARRAY_NEW 3
DUP
PUSH_INT 1
ARRAY_GET
OUTPUT
HALT
        }
    }
}

    ARRAY\_NEW 3 pops three values and creates an array [10, 20, 30],
    pushing its address.  We DUP the address (we will need it), push
    index 1, and ARRAY\_GET pops idx then arr, producing 20.

    \fculn{Push and Pop}

    ARRAY\_PUSH appends a value; ARRAY\_POP removes and returns the last:

    \hylst{\verb|
; Create empty array
ARRAY_NEW 0
; Push 100, 200, 300
DUP
PUSH_INT 100
ARRAY_PUSH
DUP
PUSH_INT 200
ARRAY_PUSH
DUP
PUSH_INT 300
ARRAY_PUSH
; Get length
DUP
ARRAY_LEN
OUTPUT
HALT
|}{%
    \indented{
        \sn{
ARRAY_NEW 0
DUP
PUSH_INT 100
ARRAY_PUSH
DUP
PUSH_INT 200
ARRAY_PUSH
DUP
PUSH_INT 300
ARRAY_PUSH
DUP
ARRAY_LEN
OUTPUT
HALT
        }
    }
}

    We push three elements onto an initially empty array, then ARRAY\_LEN
    confirms the count is 3.

    Note the pattern: ARRAY\_PUSH pops val (top) then arr (second),
    so we DUP the array address, push the value, and call ARRAY\_PUSH.


    {}\\
    \section{\textbf{Maps}}

    Maps are Robin Hood hash tables in the persistent store.  Keys and
    values are integers.

    \indented{\fancylist{
        - \textbf{MAP\_NEW}: [] → [addr] -- create empty map
        - \textbf{MAP\_SET}: [val, key, addr] → [] -- set map[key] = val
        - \textbf{MAP\_GET}: [key, addr] → [value] -- get map[key] (0 if missing)
        - \textbf{MAP\_HAS}: [key, addr] → [0/1] -- check if key exists
        - \textbf{MAP\_DEL}: [key, addr] → [0/1] -- delete key
        - \textbf{MAP\_LEN}: [addr] → [count]
        - \textbf{MAP\_KEYS}: [addr] → [arr\_addr] -- array of all keys
    }}

    \hylst{\verb|
.sym m
; Create map
MAP_NEW
PUSH_CONST 0
BIND
; Set map[1] = 100
PUSH_CONST 0
LOOKUP
PUSH_INT 1
PUSH_INT 100
MAP_SET
; Set map[2] = 200
PUSH_CONST 0
LOOKUP
PUSH_INT 2
PUSH_INT 200
MAP_SET
; Get map[1]
PUSH_CONST 0
LOOKUP
PUSH_INT 1
MAP_GET
OUTPUT
HALT
|}{%
    \indented{
        \sn{
.sym m
MAP_NEW
PUSH_CONST 0
BIND
PUSH_CONST 0
LOOKUP
PUSH_INT 1
PUSH_INT 100
MAP_SET
PUSH_CONST 0
LOOKUP
PUSH_INT 2
PUSH_INT 200
MAP_SET
PUSH_CONST 0
LOOKUP
PUSH_INT 1
MAP_GET
OUTPUT
HALT
        }
    }
}

    We create a map, store two entries, and retrieve the value at key 1.

    \hylst{\verb|
; Check map length
.sym m
MAP_NEW
PUSH_CONST 0
BIND
; Add 3 entries
PUSH_CONST 0
LOOKUP
PUSH_INT 1
PUSH_INT 10
MAP_SET
PUSH_CONST 0
LOOKUP
PUSH_INT 2
PUSH_INT 20
MAP_SET
PUSH_CONST 0
LOOKUP
PUSH_INT 3
PUSH_INT 30
MAP_SET
; Output length
PUSH_CONST 0
LOOKUP
MAP_LEN
OUTPUT
HALT
|}{%
    \indented{
        \sn{
.sym m
MAP_NEW
PUSH_CONST 0
BIND
PUSH_CONST 0
LOOKUP
PUSH_INT 1
PUSH_INT 10
MAP_SET
PUSH_CONST 0
LOOKUP
PUSH_INT 2
PUSH_INT 20
MAP_SET
PUSH_CONST 0
LOOKUP
PUSH_INT 3
PUSH_INT 30
MAP_SET
PUSH_CONST 0
LOOKUP
MAP_LEN
OUTPUT
HALT
        }
    }
}


    {}\\
    \section{\textbf{Heap Memory}}

    For raw memory access, Subnivean provides a heap: a persistent store
    of fixed-size blocks.

    \indented{\fancylist{
        - \textbf{MEM\_ALLOC}: [count] → [addr] -- allocate a block with count slots
        - \textbf{MEM\_STORE}: [val, idx, addr] → [] -- store heap[addr][idx] = val
        - \textbf{MEM\_LOAD}: [idx, addr] → [value] -- load heap[addr][idx]
        - \textbf{MEM\_LEN}: [addr] → [len] -- get block length
    }}

    \hylst{\verb|
.sym buf
; Allocate 3 slots
PUSH_INT 3
MEM_ALLOC
PUSH_CONST 0
BIND
; Store values
PUSH_CONST 0
LOOKUP
PUSH_INT 0
PUSH_INT 111
MEM_STORE
PUSH_CONST 0
LOOKUP
PUSH_INT 1
PUSH_INT 222
MEM_STORE
PUSH_CONST 0
LOOKUP
PUSH_INT 2
PUSH_INT 333
MEM_STORE
; Load slot 1
PUSH_CONST 0
LOOKUP
PUSH_INT 1
MEM_LOAD
OUTPUT
HALT
|}{%
    \indented{
        \sn{
.sym buf
PUSH_INT 3
MEM_ALLOC
PUSH_CONST 0
BIND
PUSH_CONST 0
LOOKUP
PUSH_INT 0
PUSH_INT 111
MEM_STORE
PUSH_CONST 0
LOOKUP
PUSH_INT 1
PUSH_INT 222
MEM_STORE
PUSH_CONST 0
LOOKUP
PUSH_INT 2
PUSH_INT 333
MEM_STORE
PUSH_CONST 0
LOOKUP
PUSH_INT 1
MEM_LOAD
OUTPUT
HALT
        }
    }
}

    We allocate 3 slots, store 111/222/333, and load back slot 1 (222).

    \fculn{Stack vs Heap}

    Stack values (integers, booleans) are transient -- they exist only
    while on the stack or bound in a scope.  Heap values (arrays, maps,
    memory blocks) persist in the VM's store -- they survive across
    function calls and can be shared between scopes.  When a scope is
    freed, bindings to heap addresses are dropped but the heap data
    itself persists as long as anything references it.


    {}\\
    \section{\textbf{Worked Example: GCD}}

    The Euclidean algorithm computes the greatest common divisor of two
    integers.  The method: while b is not zero, replace (a, b) with
    (b, a mod b).  When b reaches zero, a holds the GCD.

    Let us compute gcd(48, 18) = 6:

    \hylst{\verb|
.sym a
.sym b
.const " "
; a = 48
PUSH_INT 48
CELL_NEW
PUSH_CONST 0
BIND
; b = 18
PUSH_INT 18
CELL_NEW
PUSH_CONST 1
BIND
loop:
  ; if b == 0, done
  PUSH_CONST 1
  LOOKUP
  CELL_GET
  PUSH_INT 0
  EQ
  JUMP_IF done
  ; temp = a mod b
  PUSH_CONST 0
  LOOKUP
  CELL_GET
  PUSH_CONST 1
  LOOKUP
  CELL_GET
  MOD
  ; a = b
  PUSH_CONST 1
  LOOKUP
  CELL_GET
  PUSH_CONST 0
  LOOKUP
  CELL_SET
  ; b = temp (still on stack)
  PUSH_CONST 1
  LOOKUP
  CELL_SET
  JUMP loop
done:
; output a
PUSH_CONST 0
LOOKUP
CELL_GET
OUTPUT
HALT
|}{%
    \indented{
        \sn{
.sym a
.sym b
.const " "
PUSH_INT 48
CELL_NEW
PUSH_CONST 0
BIND
PUSH_INT 18
CELL_NEW
PUSH_CONST 1
BIND
loop:
PUSH_CONST 1
LOOKUP
CELL_GET
PUSH_INT 0
EQ
JUMP_IF done
PUSH_CONST 0
LOOKUP
CELL_GET
PUSH_CONST 1
LOOKUP
CELL_GET
MOD
PUSH_CONST 1
LOOKUP
CELL_GET
PUSH_CONST 0
LOOKUP
CELL_SET
PUSH_CONST 1
LOOKUP
CELL_SET
JUMP loop
done:
PUSH_CONST 0
LOOKUP
CELL_GET
OUTPUT
HALT
        }
    }
}

    Walkthrough of the first iteration:

    \indented{\fancylist{
        - a=48, b=18.  b != 0, so continue.
        - Compute 48 mod 18 = 12 (push temp=12).
        - Copy b (18) into a: now a=18.
        - Store temp (12) into b: now b=12.
        - JUMP back to loop.
    }}

    Subsequent iterations: (18,12) → (12,6) → (6,0).
    When b=0, we exit and output a=6.


    {}\\
    \section{\textbf{Worked Example: Fibonacci}}

    Iterative Fibonacci computes fib(n) by maintaining two variables:
    \textit{prev} and \textit{curr}.  Each step sets (prev, curr) to
    (curr, prev+curr).

    Let us compute fib(10) = 55:

    \hylst{\verb|
.sym prev
.sym curr
.sym i
; prev = 0, curr = 1, i = 2
PUSH_INT 0
CELL_NEW
PUSH_CONST 0
BIND
PUSH_INT 1
CELL_NEW
PUSH_CONST 1
BIND
PUSH_INT 2
CELL_NEW
PUSH_CONST 2
BIND
loop:
  ; if i > 10, done
  PUSH_CONST 2
  LOOKUP
  CELL_GET
  PUSH_INT 10
  GT
  JUMP_IF done
  ; temp = prev + curr
  PUSH_CONST 0
  LOOKUP
  CELL_GET
  PUSH_CONST 1
  LOOKUP
  CELL_GET
  ADD
  ; prev = curr
  PUSH_CONST 1
  LOOKUP
  CELL_GET
  PUSH_CONST 0
  LOOKUP
  CELL_SET
  ; curr = temp (on stack)
  PUSH_CONST 1
  LOOKUP
  CELL_SET
  ; i++
  PUSH_CONST 2
  LOOKUP
  CELL_INC
  POP
  JUMP loop
done:
PUSH_CONST 1
LOOKUP
CELL_GET
OUTPUT
HALT
|}{%
    \indented{
        \sn{
.sym prev
.sym curr
.sym i
PUSH_INT 0
CELL_NEW
PUSH_CONST 0
BIND
PUSH_INT 1
CELL_NEW
PUSH_CONST 1
BIND
PUSH_INT 2
CELL_NEW
PUSH_CONST 2
BIND
loop:
PUSH_CONST 2
LOOKUP
CELL_GET
PUSH_INT 10
GT
JUMP_IF done
PUSH_CONST 0
LOOKUP
CELL_GET
PUSH_CONST 1
LOOKUP
CELL_GET
ADD
PUSH_CONST 1
LOOKUP
CELL_GET
PUSH_CONST 0
LOOKUP
CELL_SET
PUSH_CONST 1
LOOKUP
CELL_SET
PUSH_CONST 2
LOOKUP
CELL_INC
POP
JUMP loop
done:
PUSH_CONST 1
LOOKUP
CELL_GET
OUTPUT
HALT
        }
    }
}

    The loop runs for i=2..10 (nine iterations).  Starting from fib(0)=0
    and fib(1)=1, we accumulate up to fib(10)=55.


    {}\\
    \section{\textbf{Opcode Reference}}

    Complete reference of every Subnivean instruction.  Stack effects use
    the notation [popped] → [pushed].  Operand column
    shows what the operand means (-- if none).

    \fculn{Stack Operations}

    \indented{\fancylist{
        - \textbf{NOP}: no operation
        - \textbf{POP}: [a] → [] -- discard top of stack
        - \textbf{DUP}: [a] → [a, a] -- duplicate top
        - \textbf{SWAP}: [a, b] → [b, a] -- swap top two
        - \textbf{ROT}: [a, b, c] → [b, c, a] -- rotate top three
    }}

    \fculn{Constants}

    \indented{\fancylist{
        - \textbf{PUSH\_NIL}: [] → [nil]
        - \textbf{PUSH\_TRUE}: [] → [1]
        - \textbf{PUSH\_FALSE}: [] → [0]
        - \textbf{PUSH\_INT n}: [] → [n] -- push immediate integer
        - \textbf{PUSH\_CONST n}: [] → [pool[n]] -- push from constant pool
    }}

    \fculn{Scope Operations}

    \indented{\fancylist{
        - \textbf{SCOPE\_NEW}: create child scope, enter it
        - \textbf{SCOPE\_POP}: exit to parent scope
        - \textbf{SCOPE\_CAPTURE}: [] → [scope] -- push current scope
        - \textbf{SCOPE\_RESTORE}: [scope] → [] -- restore scope
    }}

    \fculn{Bindings (Static)}

    \indented{\fancylist{
        - \textbf{BIND}: [value, sym] → [] -- bind in current scope
        - \textbf{LOOKUP}: [sym] → [value] -- search scope chain
        - \textbf{LOOKUP\_HERE}: [sym] → [value] -- current scope only
        - \textbf{SET}: [value, sym] → [] -- update existing binding
    }}

    \fculn{Bindings (Dynamic)}

    \indented{\fancylist{
        - \textbf{BIND\_DYN}: [value, str] → [] -- intern string, bind
        - \textbf{LOOKUP\_DYN}: [str] → [value] -- intern string, lookup
        - \textbf{SET\_DYN}: [value, str] → [] -- intern string, set
    }}

    \fculn{Cells}

    \indented{\fancylist{
        - \textbf{CELL\_NEW}: [value] → [cell] -- box the value
        - \textbf{CELL\_GET}: [cell] → [value] -- unbox
        - \textbf{CELL\_SET}: [value, cell] → [] -- mutate contents
        - \textbf{CELL\_INC}: [cell] → [new\_val] -- increment integer in cell
        - \textbf{CELL\_DEC}: [cell] → [new\_val] -- decrement integer in cell
    }}

    \fculn{Arithmetic}

    \indented{\fancylist{
        - \textbf{ADD}: [b, a] → [a+b]
        - \textbf{SUB}: [b, a] → [a-b]
        - \textbf{MUL}: [b, a] → [a*b]
        - \textbf{DIV}: [b, a] → [a/b]
        - \textbf{MOD}: [b, a] → [a mod b]
        - \textbf{NEG}: [a] → [-a]
        - \textbf{RAND}: [max] → [random 0..max-1]
    }}

    \fculn{Comparison}

    \indented{\fancylist{
        - \textbf{EQ}: [b, a] → [a==b ? 1 : 0]
        - \textbf{NE}: [b, a] → [a!=b ? 1 : 0]
        - \textbf{LT}: [b, a] → [a<b ? 1 : 0]
        - \textbf{GT}: [b, a] → [a>b ? 1 : 0]
        - \textbf{LE}: [b, a] → [a<=b ? 1 : 0]
        - \textbf{GE}: [b, a] → [a>=b ? 1 : 0]
    }}

    \fculn{Logic}

    \indented{\fancylist{
        - \textbf{AND}: [b, a] → [a\&\&b ? 1 : 0]
        - \textbf{OR}: [b, a] → [a||b ? 1 : 0]
        - \textbf{NOT}: [a] → [!a ? 1 : 0]
    }}

    \fculn{Control Flow}

    \indented{\fancylist{
        - \textbf{JUMP label}: unconditional jump
        - \textbf{JUMP\_IF label}: [cond] → [] -- jump if truthy
        - \textbf{JUMP\_UNLESS label}: [cond] → [] -- jump if falsy
        - \textbf{LOOP label}: backward jump
    }}

    \fculn{Functions}

    \indented{\fancylist{
        - \textbf{CLOSURE n}: [scope] → [closure] -- wrap function pool[n]
        - \textbf{CALL n}: [args..., closure] → [result] -- call with n args
        - \textbf{TAIL\_CALL n}: like CALL, reuses frame
        - \textbf{INVOKE\_DYN n}: [args..., val] → [result] -- dynamic dispatch
        - \textbf{RETURN}: return nil
        - \textbf{RETURN\_VAL}: [value] → ; return TOS
    }}

    \fculn{Arrays}

    \indented{\fancylist{
        - \textbf{ARRAY\_NEW n}: [elems...] → [arr] -- n = element count
        - \textbf{ARRAY\_GET}: [idx, arr] → [elem]
        - \textbf{ARRAY\_SET}: [val, idx, arr] → []
        - \textbf{ARRAY\_LEN}: [arr] → [len]
        - \textbf{ARRAY\_PUSH}: [val, arr] → []
        - \textbf{ARRAY\_POP}: [arr] → [val]
    }}

    \fculn{Maps}

    \indented{\fancylist{
        - \textbf{MAP\_NEW}: [] → [addr]
        - \textbf{MAP\_GET}: [key, addr] → [value]
        - \textbf{MAP\_SET}: [val, key, addr] → []
        - \textbf{MAP\_HAS}: [key, addr] → [0/1]
        - \textbf{MAP\_DEL}: [key, addr] → [0/1]
        - \textbf{MAP\_LEN}: [addr] → [count]
        - \textbf{MAP\_KEYS}: [addr] → [arr\_addr]
    }}

    \fculn{Heap Memory}

    \indented{\fancylist{
        - \textbf{MEM\_ALLOC}: [count] → [addr]
        - \textbf{MEM\_STORE}: [val, idx, addr] → []
        - \textbf{MEM\_LOAD}: [idx, addr] → [value]
        - \textbf{MEM\_LEN}: [addr] → [len]
    }}

    \fculn{Strings}

    \indented{\fancylist{
        - \textbf{CONCAT}: [b, a] → [a+b] -- string concatenation
        - \textbf{STRINGIFY}: [val] → [str] -- convert to string
        - \textbf{SYMBOL}: [str] → [sym] -- intern string as symbol
    }}

    \fculn{Output}

    \indented{\fancylist{
        - \textbf{OUTPUT}: [val] → [] -- stringify and append to output
        - \textbf{OUTPUT\_RAW n}: emit literal text from pool[n]
        - \textbf{EMIT\_CURSOR}: [row, col] → [] -- emit cursor positioning escape
    }}

    \fculn{Special}

    \indented{\fancylist{
        - \textbf{HALT}: stop execution
        - \textbf{BREAKPOINT}: debugger hook
        - \textbf{ASSERT}: [cond, msg] → [] -- error if falsy
        - \textbf{LEN}: [val] → [len] -- unified length
    }}

    \fculn{Assembler Directives}

    \indented{\fancylist{
        - \textbf{.const "text"}: add a string to the constant pool
        - \textbf{.sym name}: intern a symbol, add to the constant pool
        - \textbf{name:}: define a label (jump target)
        - \textbf{; text}: comment (ignored)
    }}

    Both .const and .sym share the same constant pool.  Indices are
    assigned sequentially: the first directive is index 0, the second is
    index 1, regardless of type.  Blank lines are ignored.

    \fculn{Instruction Format}

    Each instruction is 8 bytes: a 4-byte opcode and a 4-byte signed
    operand.  The operand is an immediate integer, a constant pool index,
    or a relative jump offset depending on the instruction.  The assembler
    handles all offset computation automatically.


@end

#target_prefix " "

#before_each
    \linebreaker{greedy}
    \setwidth{80}
    \setunicode{true}
    \setmathitalic{true}

    \macro<\indented{content}>{\indent[2]{${content}}}
    \macro<\cmd{x}>{\textbackslash{}\textit{${x}}}

    %%% Renders hy as source and rend as an example rendered output
    \macro<\hylst{hy}{rend}>{%
        \fancylisting{${hy}}

        \begin{vbox}
            \child{%
                \begin{hbox}
                    \child[3]{}
                    \child{\hrule{╭}{─}{╮}}
                    \child[2]{}
                \end{hbox}
            }
            \child{%
                \begin{hbox}
                    \child{
                        ╭──┴────────────╮
                    }
                    \child[1]{│}
                    \child[2]{}
                \end{hbox}
            }
            \child{%
                \begin{hbox}
                    \child[1]{│}
                    \child[1]{}
                    \child[15]{
                        \hyades{} Output │
                    }
                    \child{\hrule{|}{·}{|}}
                    \child[1]{│}
                    \child[2]{}
                \end{hbox}
            }
            \child{%
                \begin{hbox}
                    \child{
                        ╰──┬────────────╯
                    }
                    \child[1]{│}
                    \child[2]{}
                \end{hbox}
            }
            \child{%
                \begin{hbox}
                    \child[3]{}
                    \child[1]{\vrule[auto]{}{│}{}}
                    \child[1]{}
                    \child{${rend}}
                    \child[2]{}
                    \child[1]{\vrule[auto]{}{░}{}}
                    \child[1]{\vrule[auto]{}{│}{}}
                    \child[2]{}
                \end{hbox}
            }
            \child{
                \begin{hbox}
                    \child[3]{}
                    \child{\hrule{╰}{─}{╯}}
                    \child[2]{}
                \end{hbox}

            }
        \end{vbox}
    }

    \macro<\didyouknow{content}>{
        \vskip{1}
        \hcenter[60]{
        \hrule{}{.}{}
        ${content}
        \hrule{}{.}{}
        }
    }
#end
